-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H701> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use BLS]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H73> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use WSG]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H737> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use BUTI]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H754> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use CBFMP]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H757> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use CDF, RML]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H789> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H803> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use COGCL, COSCL]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H819> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use FRESL]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H86> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use BRPS]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H866> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use DLG]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H872> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use DRTM]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H91> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use BTF]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/H932> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use GLLY]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HACA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Anhydrite-stone and dolostone with subsidiary mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HAF> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Comprises Cefn-y-Fedw Sandstone at base (quartzose sandstone), replaced laterally by chert and mudstone in the type area; overlain by the Holywell Shales (grey and black mudstone with subsidiary sandstones) and Gwespyr Sandstone (feldspathic sandstone)."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HAHY> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Anhydrite-stone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HAMU> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone with subsidiary dolostone and sandstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HARR> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone and siltstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HAS> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Ferruginous sandstones, siltstones and shales."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HAW> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Red-brown, yellow, or yellow-mottled, very fine- to coarse-grained sandstones, commonly cross-bedded, locally micaceous, silty or argillaceous, pebbly or conglomeratic. Generally friable."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HAWL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Upper part is a creamy weathering nodular limestone in kaolinitic matrix, grey or brownish-grey muddy fine-grained limestone below."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HBMB> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HERN> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Limestone and mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HGMS> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Quartzitic sandstones, locally coarse or conglomeratic, some slates. Colours red, green, variegated. Rare plant remains marine fossils at upper boundary."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HGP> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Cyclical repetition of sandstones, siltstones, mudstones and subordinate limestones and rare coals."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HHO> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstone, fine- to medium-grained, thickly bedded, with some trough cross-bedding; seatearth at top."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HHTD> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Gravel overlain by sand; a high proportion of the gravel includes exotic clasts from Scotland, Lake District and Malvern Hills; third terrace of the River Severn, also known as the 'Main Terrace'; part of the Severn Valley Formation. [Generic description: academic papers and BGS Memoirs]."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HIDR> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Limestone and mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HIL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Limestone, high-energy ooidal and shell bioclastic grainstones, with \"non-oolitic limestone containing spar-filled shells\" (probably secondarily recrystalized and micritized limestone) at base."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Hard dark grey crinoidal oolitic bioclastic limestone with interbedded dark grey shales and mudstones."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HMBG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Predominantly mudstone and sandstone of the constituent formations: \r\n\r\nBrae Formation; \r\n\r\nCorallian Formation (Offshore); \r\n\r\nEmerald Formation; \r\n\r\nFulmar Formation; \r\n\r\nHeather Formation; \r\n\r\nKimmeridge Clay Formation (Offshore); \r\n\r\nPiper Formation; \r\n\r\nSeeley Formation; \r\n\r\nWoodward Formation."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HMMB> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone and shelly mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HMSF> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Predominantly yellowish aeolian sandstones, some deposited by sheet floods; fine- to coarse-grained, with well rounded grains. Basal beds are pebbly. Large-scale, crossbedded or laminated; rarely contorted. Some beds friable, others hard and siliceous. Contains fossil reptiles."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HOG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Crinoidal and oolitic limestone, sandstones with shales and thin coals and thin fossiliferous limestones, decalcified reddish grits and sandstones with some sandy limestones."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HOHE> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Gravel, sand and pebbly sand, variably cross-bedded to parallel laminated; clasts mostly Triassic quartzites with flints; Lake District, Scottish and Malvernian rocks."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HOL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstone, fine- to coarse-grained, part pebbly, with subordinate siltstone/mudstone; commonly in upward-fining units."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HOWH> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "The How Hill Member is composed of sand and predominantly flint gravel. It is characterised by c.30-40 per cent white or colourless quartzose rocks, persistent small percentages of Carboniferous and Rhaxella chert and traces of Spilsby Sandstone, Greensand Chert and both felsic and mafic volcanic rocks.It is marine in origin."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HRTL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use FWL, GAL]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HURD> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sand and gravel"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HVG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Crystal and lithic tuffs, agglomerates, breccias with thin interbedded shales."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HYG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstones and grey shales with Spirorbis limestones and coal seams."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/HYSH> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Hard dark-blue or bluish-green, generally mottled, shales and mudstones. Calcareous bands and nodules, and calcareous shales and mudstones occur near the top and a calcareous siltstone (yielding rich Famennian faunas locally) forms a small ridge at Hyner (SX 8404 8214) and east of Christow (SX 8407 8488). Where the Hyner Shale is within the metamorphic aureole of the Dartmoor Granite, calc-flintas are common and siliceous nodules are characteristic of the lower parts of the formation.."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/INCA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Dolostone with subsidiary limestone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/INVO> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Basalt and tuff with subsidiary mudstone and tuffaceous-mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/IRAN> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Anhydrite-stone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/ISLL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> " [Obsolete: use DAIL] Metalimestone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/JOMU> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone with subsidiary sandstone and trace dolostone and limestone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/JOSA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone, siltstone and sandstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/JRSF> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Limestone and mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/JSMU> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/JSSA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstone with subsidiary mudstone and siltstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/JUMU> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone with subsidiary dolostone and limestone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/JUSA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstone with subsidiary mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KBF> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Ripple laminated shallow marine mudstones, siltstones and fine-grained sandstones with thick coarse-grained sandstones (Knott Copy Grit and Lane Foot Sandstone)."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KBR> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "A breccia band just over a metre thick with roughly equal proportions of Precambrian, Llandovery, and Lower Carboniferous pebbles. In the upper part comprising red pebbly sandstone with coarse breccia."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KCM> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Silicate- and calcareous mudstone, interbedded with thin and more or less argillaceous limestones (calcilutite and shelly and peloidal wackestone). Locally includes coralliferous limestone bodies (knoll reef)."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KCMK> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Limestone (calcilutite and wackestone), commonly accummulated around a framework of corals, bivalves and other organisms, forming localised lenticular bodies typically less than 100m in lateral extent (\"knoll-reef\")."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KDM> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Pebble conglomerates and reddish brown sandstones. The sandstones are cross-bedded and pebbly. The conglomerates have a reddish brown sandy matrix and consist mainly of pebbles of brown or purple quartzite, with quartz conglomerate and vein quartz. (Mitchell and others, 1962)."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KEIT> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Metalimestone, mid-grey, colour-banded, generally massive but with many open joints and cavities."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KFRD> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sand and gravel. In a borehole at Timworth Green [TL 8590 6923] BGS Registered No.TL86NE/82, they had a mean composition of 5 per cent 'fines', 55 per cent sand and 40 per cent gravel, but the lithology tends to be very variable.The gravel fraction is predominantly flint."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KIS> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Fine- to medium-grained red, locally white, strongly cross-bedded sandstone with abundent millet-seed grains."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KLMB> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone and shelly mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KMMB> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KPAN> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Anhydrite-stone and mudstone with subsidiary dolostone and siltstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KPHA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Halite-stone with subsidiary mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KPSC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/KYRE> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone with subsidiary limestone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LAW> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sand, grey, loose, fine- to coarse-grained, with traces of fine gravel or sand and gravel; plant remains are present. [Generic description: Geol Soc Lond Special Publication Report 4, 2nd edition]."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LBG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Obsolete term Border Group, Lower is replaced by Ballagan Formation or Lyne Formation."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LBO> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Interbedded sandstones, siltstones and mudstones with some limestones ('cementstones'); marine faunal bands in places; local volcanic units.\r\n\r\nObsolete term Lower Border Group is replaced by Ballagan Formation or Lyne Formation."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LBS> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone, dark grey to black, blocky or shaly, calcareous, pyritic, petroliferous, with subordinate interbedded limestones and sandstones. Limestones in the lower part especially include conglomerates and turbiditic debris beds."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LCM> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Grey mudstone, siltstone and pale grey sandstone interbedded; coal seams common in upper part; mudstones with marine fossils (marine bands) present in lower part."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LCW> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "The type area west of Windermere consists of a sequence of thickly bedded, fine-grained sandstones with subordinate, muddy siltstones; the thick sandstones wedge out east of Windermere and show a lateral transition into a facies with a characteristic \"striped\" appearance consisting of laminae (0.5 mm to 15 mm) and beds of coarse-grained silt in blue-grey silty mudstone of the Brathay Flags type lithology."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LEHA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Halite-stone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LEWI> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstone with subsidiary limestone and mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LFRD> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sand and gravel, but also with beds of interbedded clay and silt.Typically about 6 per cent 'fines', 65 per cent sand and 29 per cent gravel."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LFSA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Red marls, sandstones and cornstones."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LGFL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Group of several thin (six of 0.04 to 0.14m thick in type section) probably impersistent limestone beds separated by mudstone beds (up to 0.3m thick). Limestones are hard, grey, brown-weathering, silty, bioclastic, fine- to medium-grained, with numerous bored Gryphaea and Pseudopecten. auna also includes gastropods, other bivalves, ostracods and echinoderms. Forms a weak feature."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LGRV> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sand and gravel. [Generic description: from East Anglian data]."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LGST> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "See entries for individual components."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LKSF> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mainly red-brown or purple sandstones, well-bedded, cross-stratified, micaceous, in some cases pebbly (lithic arenites), with subordinate red-brown silty mudstone ribs and conglomerate beds."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LLDD> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "An alternation of mainly marine shales and limestones with some thin coals and seatearths."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LLI> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Grey mudstones with concretionary and tabular argillaceous limestone, ironstone or sandstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LLIC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Grey, blocky and fissile, fossiliferous mudstones with some thin limestones."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LLNC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Acidic ash-flow tuff, mainly non-welded."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LLTE> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Used in the past to describe Palaeogene deposits beneath the London Clay in the London Basin, especially where the Lambeth Group and the Thanet Formation are difficult to separate, as in Essex, for example. In some places, this may include the Harwich Formation and there would be equivalent to Thanet Formation, Lambeth Group and Harwich Formation (Undifferentiated) [TSLH]."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LLU> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Silty mudstones and siltstones."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LMC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Composite consisting of two or more rock units. See the entries for the constituent units for more information."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LNF> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Alternations of bands of fossiliferous mudstone and laminated muddy siltstone with subordinate thin lenticular bands of calcareous siltstones."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LOMB> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Coal and mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LOOR> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone, olivine-basalt, sandstone and siltstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LOR> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Conglomerate and sandstone with subsidiary mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LOSD> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone, siltstone and sandstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LOXC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Fossiliferous pale grey and brown-grey bituminous mudstones with thin nodular limestones. See also the definition of the Peterborough Member (PET), and Horton (1989)."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LRF> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Dacitic lapilli tuff."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LRL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "An alternation of mainly marine shales and limestones, with some thin coals and seatearths."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LSMB> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone and shelly mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LTAN> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Anhydrite-stone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LTGL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Group of one to three, typically two, limestone beds, separated by mudstone. Lower limestone is hard grey, very shelly, including ammonites, bioclastic and about 0.25m thick.  Upper limestone is less shelly, fine, very sandy, ferruginous limestone, with pectiniids. Fauna (mainly from the lower limestone bed) also includes forams, gastropods, brachiopods, belemnites (lowest recorded in area), ostracods, echinoderms, and Chondrites burrows.  Forms a strong feature."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LUL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Dominantly a cyclical sequence of limestones and mudstones with thin coals and seatclays."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/LYM> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Interbedded silty mudstones, grey-buff, and thin fine-grained sandstones; some mass flow and slumped strata, including coarse sandstones and conglomerate."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MAE> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Grey to bluish grey siltstones with subordinate grey, light grey, yellow and white fine-grained sandstones and siltstone laminae which are parallel or ripple-laminated. Bioturbated. Rare macrofauna. Includes Dinas Sandstone Member at top of formation."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MARS> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MBG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Obsolete term Border Group, Middle is replaced by Fell Sandstone Formation, Lumsden et al, 1968; Day, 1970."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MBO> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Interbedded sandstone, siltstone and mudstone with thin limestones (cementstones) below; mainly sandstone above. Marine faunal bands in places; local volcanic beds.\r\n\r\nObsolete term Middle Border Group is replaced by Fell Sandstone Formation, Lumsden et al, 1968; Day, 1970."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MCBT> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Limestone and mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MCKL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Limestone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MCM> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Grey mudstone, siltstone and pale grey sandstone interbedded; coal seams common mudstone with marine fossils; (marine bands) present in the upper half and a single one at base."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MCW> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Consists of variable proportions of fine-grained, blue-grey, calcareous siltstones with interbedded laminated siltstone and silty mudstone. The calcareous divisions form pronounced ridges with marked cleavage."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MDGT> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "A group of grit and shales."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MDMC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "The Middleton Main Coal, Cromwell or New Hards Coal is a good quality bituminous coal that has been worked extensively in the district around Batley, Gomersal and Gildersome. its roof measures are rich in fish remains."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MGI> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Variable composition; stratified sequences within drumlins that formed during drumlinisation. [Generic description: Geol Soc Lond Special Publication Report 4, 2nd edition]."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MGT> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstone overlain by fireclays or ganisters. Coal seams are locally conspicuous and marine bands are well developed. Shale and gritstone also occur."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MILT> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "|"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MKHA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Halite-stone with subsidiary anhydrite-stone and mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MLEC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Coal, although where the deposit splits into two seams, it is separated into two by by a band of seatearth around Old Mills Colliery (364500, 155500), whereas further away from the divide this, becomes 12 m of hard mudstone and fireclay, near Greyfield Colliery (364000, 158700)."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MLI> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Siltstones, sandstones, ironstones and limestones with subsidiary mudstone or sandstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MLLL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Two grey, weathering brown, sandy, shelly limestone or highly calcareous siltstone beds up to c 0.3m thick, separated by up to 1m of mudstone. Limestone/siltstone becoming nodular in south of range. Fauna includes gastropods, brachiopds, bivalves (including numerous pectiniids and common Gryphaea), ammonites, belemnites, ostracods and echinoderms.  Forms a variably strong feature."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MOAN> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Anhydrite-stone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MOCA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Dolostone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MODS> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "The Monadh Dubh sandstone Formation consists of 4 members, but was shown as one unit on the 50k maps. From the base these members are Shellesder, A'Mharagach, Sgaorishal and Allt Dubh.\r\nThe base of the unit lies directly on the Torridonian and comprises coarse, continental-derived conglomerates. Gradually the succession fines upwards and the top 25m (two members) are dominated by fine sand and lacustrine carbonate rocks with ostracods."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MORG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Anhydrite-stone with subsidiary mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MOXC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Pale grey, green-grey calcareous mudstones with silty mudstones and calcareous siltstones. See definition of Stewartby Member (SBY)."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MRD> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Redbed sequence consisting of interbedded mudstones, sandstones and subordinate thin conglomerates with a few thin beds of Spirorbis limestone; subdivision of sequence into members based on recognition of upwards-coarsening cycles."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/MTMB> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone and shelly mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/NANN> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "East Shetland Basin: Fine- to coarse-grained, fairly well sorted, partly calcite-cemented, pebbly/granulitic, white to pale brown sandstones. Pebbles concentrations often form basal lags of upward-fining beds. Cross-bedding, wave-rippled lamination and burrows occur in places. Occasional thin mudstone beds with marine fossils also occur in some parts of the sequence, and can be recognised in geophysical logs by their distinct gamma-ray peaks (a large peak is often seen in the middle part of the formation). \r\n\r\nBeryl Embayment and South Viking Graben: The formation is composed almost entirely of fine-to coarse-grained, quartzose, mud-free sandstones. They are often kaolinitic. The sandstones are stacked in c. 8 m-thick, occasionally upward coarsening, units.  Sedimentary structures and bioturbation are rare.  Near the top of the formation a unit of muddy sandstone, with carbonaceous wisps and laminae, causing relatively high gamma values, often occurs. Thin beds of pebbly, silty mudstone cause distinct gamma-ray peaks near the base and the middle of the formation."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/NBG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Fine grained uncleaved sandstones (often deformed) and roughly cleaved sandy shales."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/NCL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Grey sandstones, siltstones and mudstones with minor reddened strata; coals few and thin; some thin limestones near base."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/NE> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Black shales, flaggy greywackes and shales, conglomerates, grits, limestones and mudstones."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/NFLM> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "A pale to dark grey, argillaceous, shelly, bioclastic limestone,  interpreted to be of marine origin."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/NHM> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstones and siltstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/NTC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstone, pinkish red or buff-grey, medium- to coarse-grained, pebbly, cross-bedded, friable; subordinate lenticular beds of reddish brown mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/OMS> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Fine- to coarse-grained (generally medium-) cross bedded and flat bedded sandstones, generally friable.  In West Cumbria sandstones are aeolian, but offshore the Ormskirk Sandstone is dominated by fluvial sandstones, with aeolian interbeds. Details of lithology in the type area are not known, other than a description of 'coarse sandstone'."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/ORCA> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone, siltstone and sandstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/OS> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Fine- to medium-grained sandstone, weathering to sand near surface. Sandstones locally micaceous and cross-bedded. Thin units of hard intraformational conglomerate; lenticular beds of reddish brown clay or mudstone locally; calcretes at some horizons. Lenticular pebble bed units mapped in the Exeter district."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PEL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Massive to rubbly pale skeletal limestones with intercalated ochreous weathering, thin, clay palaeosol horizons; a widely recognised 3m-thick shale bed occurs 20m above the base of the formation."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PENS> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Fine-grained sandy clay, clayey fine-grained sand and thin beds of fine-grained sand."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PET2> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Predominantly clay with gravel seams"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PGHY> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Anhydrite-stone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PLB> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "The Plateau Beds Formation unconformably overlies the Brownstones Formation. A slight angular discordance between the formations is present on Bannau Sir Gaer and Fan Brycheiniog (Allen, 1964; Lovell, 1975). Descriptions were given by Hall et al. (1973) and Taylor and Thomas (1975). The formation comprises red-brown and purple quartzitic sandstones, locally pebbly and conglomeratic, and interbeds of red-brown mudstone. The sandstones are generally harder than the Brownstones, and form resistant cappings to the Brecon Beacons."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PLWF> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Poorly cemented, reddish-brown sandstone with thin beds of red mudstone and conglomerate."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PN> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Trachytic and andesitic tuffs, with locally conglomeratic tuffaceous sediments. NOTE: The definition follows the usage on British Geological Survey 1:25 000 Special Sheet SM72 (St Davids), 1973, which in turn derives from Green, JFN. 1908.The computer code PV already exists for 'Pebidian Volcanic Series (undifferentieated)'."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PNO> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sandstones, siltstones, mudstones, shales and turbidites. Fossiliferous bands with shelly faunas and graptolites. See constituent formations (Lower Camregan Grits, Wood Burn, Maxwellston Mudstones, Upper Camregan Grits, Penkill, Protovirgularia Grits, Lauchlan, Drumyork Flags, Blair Shale, Knockgardner, Straiton Grits.)"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PNWL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Stacked cyclic sequence of dark grey limestones in which shelly and crinoidal grainstones are the major components; beds are locally sandy, and chert layers and nodules are abundant. Many cycles are truncated by subaerial surfaces underlain by nodular limestones and overlain by seatearths and thin coals."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/POGF> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "breccia of mudstone and sandstone with rafts of quartzite and limestone"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/POW> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Obsolete term Powillimount Beds is replaced by Powillimount Sandstone Member."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PRR> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Rhyolitic lavas and flinty rhyolitic tuffs."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PSO> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone and sandstone: see constituent formations (Tralorg, Saugh Hill Grits, Pencleuch Shale)."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/PVL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use PN] \r\n\r\nTrachytic and andesitic tuffs and tuffaceous sediments, locally conglomeratic. NOTE: The definition follows the usage on British Geological 1:25 000 Special Sheet SM72 (St Davids), 1973, which in turn derives from GREEN, JFN, 1908.The computer code PV already exists for 'Pebidian Volcanic Series (undifferentiated)'"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/QC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Red-brown medium- to coarse-grained pebbly sandstones and quartz pebble conglomerates with some mudstone interbeds."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/QCG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "An upper portion of sandstones with alternations of marl, and a lower portion of lenticular quartz-conglomerate beds with sandstones, grits and quartzites."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/R1A2> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone. Kinderscoutian."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/R2A1> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone. Marsdenian."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/R2B4> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone. Marsdenian."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/R2C1> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone. Marsdenian."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/RDBN> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Sequence of limestones, mudstones and silty sandstones."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/RDM> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Red siltstones and mudstones with subordinate sandstones. Correlative of Red Marl Group is the Milford Haven Group."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/RG> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Red mudstones and silty mudstones with calcretes and sandstones. Townsend Tuff Bed 100m from top; Bishop's Frome Limestone at top."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/RGST> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/ROHL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Halite-stone with subsidiary anhydrite-stone and mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/RSCC> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Part of the composite (Conglass Conglomerate Formation) was entered in error. The code/name combination is obsolete and should not be used, being replaced by Raebeg Sandstone Formation And Conglass Sandstone Formation (Undifferentiated) [RSCS]."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/RSL> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Purple slightly micaceous slates with crinoid debris and other fossil fragments (including bivalves, clymenids and rare trilobites and ostracods), green slates and black siliceous slates. A prominent horizon of calcareous laminated siltstone is present at the top of the unit."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/RTSZ> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Mudstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/RVB> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Limestone, predominantly calcilutitic and more or less argillaceous, interbedded with calcareous mudstone and calcareous siltstone."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/RWD> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "Brick-red mudstones, poorly-micaceous, usually calcareous, with sandstones and limestones."@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S110> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use TWD]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S114> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use ACRL]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S115> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use TYL]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S116> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use GILS]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S126> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use PPTMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S127> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use KNYMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S13> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use CER]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S135> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use CCT]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S138> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use LTMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S142> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use CHSI]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S148> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use 5RDMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S149> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use FORMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S15> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use BCWC]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S150> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use MCHMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S160> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use ULOL]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S165> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use MBDMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S167> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use KMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S168> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use SHMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S172> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use BGN, TYN, INV]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S184> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use DBFB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S190> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use AG]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S232> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Obsolete: use MANC]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S235> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use CCDMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S236> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use DUKMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S239> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use TONMB]"@en .
-<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Lexicon/NamedRockUnit/S255> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/ref/Lexicon/hasLithologyDescription> "[Duplicate: use RLMB]"@en .
